In fact, it was the humble garden that first encouraged humans to make the great leap from roaming hunter-gatherers to settled farmers around 10,000 years ago, as jungle plots gave way to fenced enclosures and crops. The whole history of humanity is tied up with gardening, meaning that these spaces have changed dramatically over time and across cultures. We take a closer look.\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e\u003cblockquote\u003eThe biblical garden\u003c/blockquote\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe Garden of Eden has been an obsession for western artists for centuries. Perhaps one of the best-known depictions comes from \u003ca href\u003d\"/entity/m0cdn_\"\u003eHieronymus Bosch’s\u003c/a\u003e triptych \u003ci\u003eThe Garden of Earthly Delights\u003c/i\u003e (1500-1505). Here, life before the Fall is shown on the left-hand screen as a serene paradise, while in the main central panel we get a glimpse of what happens when humans are left to their own devices (clue: it’s sinful). Free will makes for an orgy of indulgence, but there are consequences, as shown in the far right panel’s hellscape of fire and monstrous demons.\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86fN3DP0AQCevV_JKSzxpfioOhsZbEzVPagz31wfOCVWYnLoUaenvAVxqaAUL6m-WU6uaLghLPI",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eThe Garden of Earthly Delights by Hieronymus Bosch (From the collection of Royal Museums of Fine Arts of Belgium)\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86fN3DP0AQCevV_JKSzxpfioOhsZbEzVPagz31wfOCVWYnLoUaenvAVxqaAUL6m-WU6uaLghLPI",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003e\u003cblockquote\u003eThe Hanging Gardens of Babylon\u003c/blockquote\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe only Wonder of the Ancient World that we don’t have an exact modern day location for are the Hanging Gardens of Babylon. They were probably not in the city of Babylon at all (close to modern day Baghdad) but are more likely to have been miles north in Nineveh (near Iraq’s Turkish border). What’s more, they may not have been conventional gardens either, but rather a many-stepped palace with greenery growing on the roofs. This was quite a feat in the arid climate of ancient Mesopotamia and it’s thought the gardens were irrigated by an early version of Archimedes\u0026#39; Screw, which allows the transportation of water uphill. The fact that they were written about by several classical authors means that they almost certainly existed, but we may never know what they really looked like.\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86eVFEjA_P1oUBvX8lLNulgxlOV8RRy6q4PGEuj-UOghPhl_8gExRK_XZW5bso4ha0vxfMdFaw",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eArc Reco Seven Wonders 1 Colussus of Rhodes Hanging Gardens of Babylon Mausoleum Artemesia (From the collection of LIFE Photo Collection)\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86eVFEjA_P1oUBvX8lLNulgxlOV8RRy6q4PGEuj-UOghPhl_8gExRK_XZW5bso4ha0vxfMdFaw",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003e\u003cblockquote\u003eThe Persian garden\u003c/blockquote\u003e\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eFormal gardens were elevated to an art form in Islamic culture, refined for centuries under the Persian Empire. Known as \u003ci\u003echahar bagh\u003c/i\u003e, these walled spaces tended to follow a strict plan that fanned out from a central fountain. It was at this central point that four rivers or watercourses met, representing the four rivers of paradise. You can still find exquisite examples of \u003ci\u003echahar bagh\u003c/i\u003e across former Persian domains, from Granada to Iran, but perhaps the best-known example is the Taj Mahal in India. Persian rugs were often decorated with the same geometric \u003ci\u003echahar bagh\u003c/i\u003e layout, providing a portable piece of paradise for elites to lounge on.\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86eKJl0JJY1h-3fNMr4XrllLfLG1e7p70I6eEVOgUG64NMOSoge9z3dlKdEtH2E866PX2zVUlIA",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eA Ruler in a Garden Pavilion Surrounded by Courtiers and Attendants (From the collection of Freer and Sackler Galleries)\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86eKJl0JJY1h-3fNMr4XrllLfLG1e7p70I6eEVOgUG64NMOSoge9z3dlKdEtH2E866PX2zVUlIA",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003e\u003cblockquote\u003eThe Japanese garden\u003c/blockquote\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnother cultural tradition that turned gardens into an otherworldly experience came from the Far East. Japan’s \u003ci\u003enihon teien\u003c/i\u003e don\u0026#39;t follow the same geometric patterns as the Persian \u003ci\u003echahar bagh\u003c/i\u003e, but they still encode a huge amount of information about Japanese culture. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eBlending natural elements such as weathered rocks and bubbling streams with manmade pagodas and bridges, these formal gardens seem haphazard, but are in fact governed by Zen philosophy. The temple garden shown here was found in the foothills of Kyoto and shows the meandering layout of a classic \u003ci\u003enihon teien\u003c/i\u003e, combining religious buildings with places of contemplation.\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86dDM82h1VCcLjWB0-AiwlbSBOwObXxEnHVFLm5lc7amur4SNS453HksjtflcGHHk2OZxdvwpA",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eFive Hundred Arhats by Itō Jakuchū (From the collection of National Gallery of Victoria)\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86dDM82h1VCcLjWB0-AiwlbSBOwObXxEnHVFLm5lc7amur4SNS453HksjtflcGHHk2OZxdvwpA",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003e\u003cblockquote\u003eThe Baroque garden\u003c/blockquote\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eBefore the \u003ca href\u003d\"/entity/m0194x\"\u003eBaroque\u003c/a\u003e period, European gardens had retained echoes of their working roots, with herb beds and wild flower borders. Versailles changed all this. The grand project of France’s Sun King Louis XIV turned the European garden into a display of power and politics, with sweeping grand avenues, huge feats of engineering and intricate geometric planting all designed to show the owner’s mastery over nature. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe King’s landscape architect \u003ca href\u003d\"/entity/m02jsdq\"\u003eAndré Le Nôtre\u003c/a\u003e referenced classical and Renaissance gardens in his design for Versailles, but pumped everything to a scale never before seen on the continent. This was gardening as theatre, forcing everyone who entered to become an actor in the owner’s personal play.\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86eSycq-A3-pAZ6XbZNde5kLVTEdSe7gX513s2cswifUZRVflmDBsz8pWw_0QxOoA5QTtIk_LQ",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eView of the Palace and Gardens of Versailles by Pierre Patel (From the collection of Palace of Versailles)\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86eSycq-A3-pAZ6XbZNde5kLVTEdSe7gX513s2cswifUZRVflmDBsz8pWw_0QxOoA5QTtIk_LQ",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003e\u003cblockquote\u003eReclaiming wilderness\u003c/blockquote\u003e\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eCenturies of horticultural formality took their toll on a European audience and by the early 20th century, artists were yearning for a return to the wilderness. This desire can be seen in \u003ca href\u003d\"/entity/m02rdf6\"\u003eHenri Rousseau’s\u003c/a\u003e masterpiece \u003ci\u003eThe Dream\u003c/i\u003e (1910), where a reclining nude awakes in a lush tropical jungle. Rousseau never actually visited the tropics but was inspired by visits to Paris’s various zoos, museums and hot houses, allowing him to imagine a world returned to nature. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThese urges were also expressing themselves at the same time on the other side of the Atlantic, with the founding of the National Park Service in the USA in 1916. We like to think of the mighty expanse of Yellowstone and Yosemite as unbridled nature, but they are, in fact, carefully managed environments: gardens on a scale the Sun King could only dream Aphids feed on plant sap, which is very rich in sugars, but has few proteins. The aphids remove the protein and release most of the sugars in the form of so-called \u0026quot;honeydew\u0026quot; secretions. When cars parked under trees become amazingly sticky: This was the action of the aphids, not the tree itself! Honey dew is the most important carbohydrate source of many ants. The relation between aphids and ants is often a mutualism: These ants protect the aphids against predators like ladybugs, even move them to new leaves, and actively milk the aphids by stroking them with their antennae.\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86fmPRMlysl16Onns_SxwPTPhGz5q7VcXB5oOoQpfE-limb2l6zp1SO6ArzkCbJqDHUJRgEtUaFF",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eThe Brazilian treehopper (\u003ci\u003eBocydium globulare\u003c/i\u003e) is one of the most incredible animals of the world. Whereas in some insect orders like beetles or butterflies larvae and adults are strongly dissimilar, and the larvae form a chrysalis to be fully transformed in a process called metamorphosis, the larvae of the true bugs (Heteroptera) and many other insect orders look immediately similar to the adults. They become more and more similar with each ecdysis (which occurs five times in the case of this species). \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe Sloe Bug feeds on flowers and fruits of many species (especially from the rose family, like cherries or plums). Because when sucking plant saps it also injects saliva, the fruits often become unpalatable for humans.\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86cGc4RsW6Enm6LQXmVcxj5b0OrOXQfk8e1MmioBH7l_47PLP7NiDK4rzgWnVNCdZbBy6d-nBQeK",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eOnly the adults have fully developed wings.\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86cCoaSJqkPeGtZo9UnaQZVLSByOqczjk3OmP4wTKzllHS-kFPKhDGMCs27WI4SSNRj3nlZCvjM",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eAn insect model of the wheat weevil (\u003ci\u003eSitophilus granarius\u003c/i\u003e) created by Alfred Keller. This weevil is a constant follower of humankind since the early stone age and one of the most feared pests of stored products.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe chewing mouthparts are at the tip of elongated snout. The females eat tiny holes into grain kernels, lay an egg, and close the hole with a secreted substance. The larvae feed mainly on cereal products (flour, rolled oats, whole kernels, but also pasta). The adults can place several 100 eggs next to the tiniest of openings in packaging. Freshly hatched, the larvae are only 1 mm long and much thinner, being able to enter many resealable household packages through tiny openings that usually remain. A mixture is made of soft clay soil and rice chaff, materials that can be found almost anywhere. This mud is worked to remove any air bubbles, and formed to make the core of whatever it is that\u0026#39;s being fired. In this case, a small bowl.\u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86fOVMqQIscEHmy9548rF6q8TBpau-L2JpKxCfdFcPdFYEcC0EIdsVbZOuTz83wEH6nqbtNrPSk",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eThe clay core is left to harden under the hot sun while the wax is collected and worked into sheets and ribbons. The wax forms a \u0026#39;positive\u0026#39;, or exact copy, of the metalwork design. This layer has to be particularly soft, yet applied with firm pressure, otherwise it won\u0026#39;t capture all the details of the wax. edges.\u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86eM6T7aKIsq1LIFnvx3w-nc-cdWDFolyNDxm7mjjkmk60-U3qH_3hu50oUFfeOxTL-2sZsdxso",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eEach mould requires a = ["stella.edit.sect",null,42,null,null,null,[[["stella.common.cobject","Vincent van Gogh was born 170 years ago today","Vincent Willem van Gogh was a Dutch Post-Impressionist painter who posthumously became one of the most famous and influential figures in Western art history. In a decade, he created about 2,100 artworks, including around 860 oil paintings, most of which date from the last two years of his life. They include landscapes, still lifes, portraits and self-portraits, and are characterised by bold colours and dramatic, impulsive and expressive brushwork that contributed to the foundations of modern art. Not commercially successful, he struggled with severe depression and poverty, eventually leading to his suicide at age thirty-seven.\nBorn into an upper-middle-class family, Van Gogh drew as a child and was serious, quiet, and thoughtful. As a young man, he worked as an art dealer, often traveling, but became depressed after he was transferred to London. He turned to religion and spent time as a Protestant missionary in southern Belgium. He drifted in ill health and solitude before taking up painting in 1881, having moved back home with his parents. His younger brother Theo supported him financially, and the two kept a long correspondence by Walker. Just who was she? Born shortly after the end of slavery, Madam Walker (born Sarah Breedlove) is said to be the nation’s first self-made female millionaire. Orphaned at age seven and widowed with a daughter at twenty, Walker earned fortune and fame by building a prosperous beauty empire, best known for its hair care products. As a businesswoman, she employed thousands of African-American women who would have otherwise been relegated to low-paying jobs.\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86dzOjQBN1O6c3DO4-1lVuIoG-bkmEjmbRJhH0XXqpDicTHH6YMaXodEpi3DOIoc4maWN608Lic",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eMadam Walker was also a philanthropist and passionate public speaker. At significant conventions sponsored by major black organizations, she was often the only woman at the podium alongside Booker T. Washington and other black leaders.\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86dzOjQBN1O6c3DO4-1lVuIoG-bkmEjmbRJhH0XXqpDicTHH6YMaXodEpi3DOIoc4maWN608Lic",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eWalker flourished as an entrepreneur despite the odds, before Women’s Suffrage and long before the Civil Rights Movement. Her life is captured in one of her most famous statements: “I am a woman from the cotton fields of the South. I was promoted to the washtub. I was promoted to the kitchen. I promoted myself to the business of hair…on my own ground.”\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86dzOjQBN1O6c3DO4-1lVuIoG-bkmEjmbRJhH0XXqpDicTHH6YMaXodEpi3DOIoc4maWN608Lic",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eSonya Clark’s decision to assemble the portrait out of combs was a powerful choice. As she recently explained, “I used 3,840 fine-toothed pocket combs to assemble this image of Walker. Combs speak to Walker’s career as a pioneer of hair care. I also used them because they capture our national legacy of hair culture, and the gender and race politics of hair.\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86dzOjQBN1O6c3DO4-1lVuIoG-bkmEjmbRJhH0XXqpDicTHH6YMaXodEpi3DOIoc4maWN608Lic",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eAs disposable objects, they parallel the low social status of African-American women born in the late 1800s. She is a first-generation American and has drawn extensively upon her Caribbean, Scottish, and African ancestry in her work. Her maternal grandmother, a professional tailor, taught Clark how to sew and helped instill an appreciation for craft and the value of the handmade. Her interest in hair emerged at an early age: “When I was growing up in D.C., my family lived across the street from the Ambassador of Benin and his family of fourteen. They lived in a large mansion and always welcomed us. class="M2QpMe"><div><svg width="24px" height="24px" viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="PwQuIe"><path d="M17 12h-5v5h5v-5zM16 1v2H8V1H6v2H5c-1.11 0-1.99.9-1.99 2L3 19c0 1.1.89 2 2 2h14c1.1 0 2-.9 2-2V5c0-1.1-.9-2-2-2h-1V1h-2zm3 18H5V8h14v11z"/></svg>Today in history</div></span><h3 class="icXnic" title="Vincent van Gogh was born 170 years ago today">Vincent van Gogh was born 170 years ago today</h3><h4 class="gDqesd" title="Vincent Willem van Gogh was a Dutch Post-Impressionist painter who posthumously became one of the most famous and influential figures in Western art history. In a decade, he created about 2,100 artworks, including around 860 oil paintings, most of which date from the last two years of his life. They include landscapes, still lifes, portraits and self-portraits, and are characterised by bold colours and dramatic, impulsive and expressive brushwork that contributed to the foundations of modern art. Not commercially successful, he struggled with severe depression and poverty, eventually leading to his suicide at age thirty-seven.
Born into an upper-middle-class family, Van Gogh drew as a child and was serious, quiet, and thoughtful. As a young man, he worked as an art dealer, often traveling, but became depressed after he was transferred to London. He turned to religion and spent time as a Protestant missionary in southern Belgium. He drifted in ill health and solitude before taking up painting in 1881, having moved back home with his parents. His younger brother Theo supported him financially, and the two kept a long correspondence by letter.">Vincent Willem van Gogh was a Dutch Post-Impressionist painter who posthumously became one of the most famous and influential figures in Western art history. In a decade, he created about 2,100 artworks, including around 860 oil paintings, most of which date from the last two years of his life. They include landscapes, still lifes, portraits and self-portraits, and are characterised by bold colours and dramatic, impulsive and expressive brushwork that contributed to the foundations of modern art. Not commercially successful, he struggled with severe depression and poverty, eventually leading to his suicide at age thirty-seven.
Born into an upper-middle-class family, Van Gogh drew as a child and was serious, quiet, and thoughtful. As a young man, he worked as an art dealer, often traveling, but became depressed after he was transferred to London. He turned to religion and spent time as a Protestant missionary in southern Belgium. He drifted in ill health and solitude before taking up painting in 1881, having moved back home with his parents. His younger brother Theo supported him financially, and the two kept a long correspondence by letter.</h4><div class="v71GJc">Learn more</div></div></span></a><div class="cCNe0" jscontroller="acWgwb"
